**The dependent variable in this dataset id the OD1000 which represents the drug overdose rate. 
**it is dependent because it is continous, and represents the outcome we are trying to explain in this set 


**the second independent variable is region // tests whether overdose rates differ by geographic region


**Hypothesis: Overdose rates differ significantly across regions 

**Estimate model 
encode region, gen(region_id)
regress OD1000 datatimeperiod 
tab region_id
list region in 1/10

describe OD1000 datatimeperiod
regress OD1000 region_id
summarize OD1000 
*after running we see that 12.7% of variation in overdose rates
*this set is marginally signifcant as it is slightly above 0.05
**the average overdose rate in the baseline region is about 67.14 per 100,000
**overall the regression shows that 13% of the variation in overdose mortality across the different regions 

// NOW CREATE A SCATTER PLOT// 
twoway ///
(scatter OD1000 region_id, ///
    msize(medium) ///
    mcolor(navy)) ///
(lfit OD1000 region_id, ///
    lcolor(maroon) ///
    lwidth(medthick)), ///
title("Regional Differences in Overdose Rates (2021)") ///
xtitle("Region (Encoded Categories)") ///
ytitle("Overdose Rate per 100,000") ///
legend(order(1 "Observed Values" 2 "Fitted Regression Line"))

// the scatter plot shows a downward trend in overdose rates across regions. this pattern aligns with the regression results
// the plot shows that overall rates differ within different regions which agrees with our hypothesis

//MARGINS PLOT // 
regress OD1000 i.region_id
margins region_id
marginsplot, ///
title("Predicted Overdose Rates by Region (2021)") ///
xtitle("Region") ///
ytitle("Predicted Overdose Rate per 100,000")
**The margins plot allows us to see the predicted overdose per region and their confidence intervals. From the margins plot we find that region explains only limited portions of variation

*EXPORTING REGRESSION TABLE 
ssc install estout, replace
regress OD1000 i.region_id
**this estimated a linear regression model / if overdose rates differ across region
est store Model1
estimates dir
** by saving the Model1 we saved those results in memory under this model which will allow us to export it later
esttab Model1 using "OD_regression_table.rtf", ///
replace se ///
star(* 0.10 ** 0.05 *** 0.01) ///
title("Overdose Rate Regression by Region (2021)") ///
label

**this exported table now contains the Rsquared, standard errors, coefficients into a professional place that can be easily accessed 
**preps the results for policy interpretation

